    <!-- Start of Worksheet -->
    <worksheet xml:id="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation">
        <title>Explore: Scientific Notation</title>

        <!-- Objectives -->
        <objectives>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    Reinforce your ability to convert between standard and scientific notation and interpret the meaning of powers of ten in real-world and scientific contexts.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </objectives>
        <!-- Introduction -->
        <introduction>
            <p>
                This worksheet is designed to help you explore the concept of scientific notation in physics.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <!-- Page 01 -->
        <page>
            <pagebreak/> 
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 01 -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The influenze virus can have a diameter of about 0.000000099 meters.
                        Convert 0.000000099 to scientific notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        The decimal point would need to move to the right by 8 places.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>9.9 \times 10^{-8}</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        To write 0.000000099 in scientific notation, move the decimal point <em>eight places to the right</em> to place it after the first nonzero digit.
                        This gives "9.9".
                        Since the decimal moved right by eight places, the exponent on 10 is -8.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>0.000000099 = 9.9 \times 10^{-8}</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 02 -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A strand of human hair is about 0.00007 meters in diameter.
                        Convert 0.00007 to scientific notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        The decimal point would need to move to the right by 5 places.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>7.0 \times 10^{-5}</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        To write 0.00007 in scientific notation, move the decimal point <em>five places to the right</em> to place it after the first nonzero digit.
                        This gives "7.0".
                        Since the decimal moved right by five places, the exponent on 10 is -5.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>0.00007 = 7.0 \times 10^{-5}</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 03 -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A grain of sand can be about 0.0012 meters in diameter.
                        Convert 0.0012 to scientific notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        The decimal point would need to move to the right by 3 places.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>1.2 \times 10^{-3}</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        To write 0.0012 in scientific notation, move the decimal point <em>three places to the right</em> to place it after the first nonzero digit.
                        This gives "1.2".
                        Since the decimal moved right by three places, the exponent on 10 is -3.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>0.0012 = 1.2 \times 10^{-3}</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 04 -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        An average adult human might be about 1.75 meters tall.
                        Convert 1.75 to scientific notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        The decimal point would need to move to the left by 0 places.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>1.75 \times 10^{0}</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        To write 1.75 in scientific notation, the decimal is already after the first nonzero digit, so we don’t need to move it.
                        That means the exponent on 10 is 0.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>1.75 = 1.75 \times 10^{0}</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 05 -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The Empire State Building in New York City is about <m>3.81 \times 10^{2}</m> meters tall.
                        Convert <m>3.81 \times 10^{2}</m> to standard notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        A positive exponent means move the decimal to the right.
                        Move it 2 places to the right.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        381
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>3.81 \times 10^{2}</m> means move the decimal point 2 places to the right: <m>3.81 → 38.1 → 381.</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>3.81 \times 10^{2} = 381</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 06 -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Mount Everest is approximately <m>8.85 \times 10^{3}</m> meters tall.
                        Convert <m>8.85 \times 10^{3}</m> to standard decimal notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        Move the decimal point 3 places to the right.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        8850
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>8.85 \times 10^{3}</m> means move the decimal 3 places to the right: <m>8.85 → 88.5 → 885 → 8850</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>8.85 \times 10^{3} = 8850</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 07 -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The Earth's diameter is about <m>1.27 \times 10^{7}</m> meters.
                        Convert <m>1.27 \times 10^{7}</m> to standard notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        Move the decimal 7 places to the right.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        12,700,000
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>1.27 \times 10^{7}</m> means move the decimal 7 places to the right: <m>1.27 → 12.7 → 127 → … → 12,700,000</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>1.27 \times 10^{7} = 12,700,000</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 08 -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The average distance from Earth to the Sun is about <m>1.496 \times 10^{11}</m> meters.
                        Convert <m>1.496 \times 10^{11}</m> to standard decimal notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        Move the decimal 11 places to the right.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        149,600,000,000
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>1.496 \times 10^{11}</m> means move the decimal 11 places to the right: <m>1.496 → 14.96 → 149.6 → … → 149,600,000,000</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>1.496 \times 10^{11} = 149,600,000,000</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
        </page>


